outlooksByWeek.1: De'Von Achane appears healthy and has minimal competition for touches in the Dolphins backfield ahead of a Week 1 matchup at Indianapolis. Achane nursed a calf issue throughout preseason but looks cleared for heavy usage in both the rushing and passing attack against a defense that allowed the 11th most fantasy points to running backs a year ago. Jaylen Wright (leg) is unlikely to play, leaving only rookie Ollie Gordon as a potential touchdown vulture to cap Achane's upside. He remains an elite option when healthy.
outlooksByWeek.2: De'Von Achane could face an uphill battle in Week 2 when the Dolphins host the Patriots. Achane logged an impressive 7.9 yards per carry last Sunday and scored on one of his three receptions, but Miami's offense looked lost in the passing game. The Patriots can stack the box, and they shut down Las Vegas rookie Ashton Jeanty last week, allowing just 2.1 yards per carry. Achane is arguably the best option in this dysfunctional offense, and his volume should keep the floor stable, and the ceiling is through the roof if something clicks with the aerial attack.

player.seasonOutlook: One of the rising stars in fantasy, Achane is entering his third NFL season after an impressive 2024, in which he registered only the 12th instance over the last decade of a player producing 200-plus carries and 75-plus receptions in a single season. Achane has now scored at least 11 TDs in both NFL seasons and paced all RBs in routes, catches, yards and receiving TDs last season. He also put size concerns aside, appearing in 17 games and finishing ninth among RBs in snaps. Achane's play plummeted when Tua Tagovailoa was sidelined (9.8 fantasy PPG), but he was elite when his QB was under center (22.6), which is the more relevant number with Tagovailoa back for 2025. Achane's dual-threat ability locks him in as a solid fantasy RB1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Davante Adams will kick off his 13th NFL season in a new uniform, as he'll feature with the Rams against Houston in Week 1. Adams has seen a drop in production over the past two years, but a late-career bounce-back could be in the works with Matthew Stafford now throwing balls to him. Puka Nacua remains the Rams' WR1, but Stafford has shown an ability to feed two top wideouts in the past when Cooper Kupp was on the club. The Texans gave up 21 receiving TDs to wideouts last year, second-most in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Davante Adams will look to further establish chemistry with Rams QB Matthew Stafford in a Week 2 matchup against the Titans. Adams had a decent regular-season debut with Los Angeles, gathering four of eight targets for 51 receiving yards. However, it was clear that Puka Nacua remains Stafford's favorite target, as the pair connected for a 10-130-0 line on 11 targets. Nacua's target dominance could keep Adams' ceiling mildly limited, though Stafford has shown the ability to feed multiple wideouts when Nacua and Cooper Kupp were paired together in recent campaigns. The Titans were much better against the pass than the run in Week 1, giving up 151 yards on the ground to 176 through the air, so the Rams could look to expose that vulnerability in Week 2.

player.seasonOutlook: Adams signed with the Rams and figures to operate as the team's de facto Cooper Kupp replacement opposite Puka Nacua. Adams' age (32) is an obvious red flag, but he didn't show signs of slowing down last season. Despite missing three games and being traded, Adams delivered five top-10 fantasy weeks, which tied for fourth among WRs. Adams has now finished top 15 in fantasy PPG each of the past 10 seasons and, while he won't be the No. 1 target in Los Angeles, there are more than enough targets to go around in Sean McVay's scheme with Matthew Stafford under center (the Rams have led the NFL in WR targets each of the last two seasons). He's no longer an elite fantasy option, but Adams is a fine WR2 target with back-end WR1 upside.

outlooksByWeek.1: Jordan Addison will miss the Vikings' first three games of the regular season due to a suspension, beginning Week 1 on the road against Chicago. In his absence, Adam Thielen and Jalen Nailor figure to benefit from increased targets behind Justin Jefferson and TE T.J. Hockenson.
outlooksByWeek.2: Jordan Addison will serve the second contest of his three-game suspension as the Vikings prepare for a matchup against the Falcons on Sunday Night Football in Week 2. In his stead, Adam Thielen and Jalen Nailor will handle increased roles behind top wideout Justin Jefferson. By the time Addison is back on the field, quarterback J.J. McCarthy will have had a chance to have gotten more comfortable at the NFL level, though it'll be notable that the two will have missed crucial opportunities to build chemistry across the first month of the regular season.

player.seasonOutlook: Addison returns for Year 3 in Minnesota having finished 23rd and 21st, respectively, in fantasy PPG during his first two NFL campaigns. Addison has been a TD machine, scoring 10 times in both seasons, which has helped offset underwhelming volume. He finished both seasons 25th or lower among WRs in targets, receptions and yards, as well as 40th or lower in target share. That led to boom/bust production last season, as he scored 43% of his fantasy points in three games and was held to single digits in seven of 15 outings. Addison is suspended three games to begin the 2025 season, but once he's on the field, he will continue battling for looks with Justin Jefferson and T.J. Hockenson. His late-season target surge (eight-plus in seven of his final eight games) provides optimism that he can sustain WR3 numbers, especially in Kevin O'Connell's pass-friendly scheme.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brandon Aiyuk will begin the season on the PUP list, so he isn't going to play in San Francisco's Week 1 matchup against Seattle. That should leave plenty of targets for second-year WR Ricky Pearsall as well as Jauan Jennings, though the latter is iffy to suit up due to a calf injury and contract dispute.
outlooksByWeek.2: Brandon Aiyuk remains on the PUP list while recovering from a knee injury, so he won't play in San Francisco's Week 2 contest against New Orleans. Jauan Jennings isn't certain to suit up due to a shoulder issue, so Ricky Pearsall could lead the 49ers' wideout corps versus the Saints.

player.seasonOutlook: Aiyuk is back in San Francisco for his sixth NFL campaign, but he's expected to miss roughly half of the season after suffering a torn ACL and MCL in October. Aiyuk had just received a contract extension, which followed back-to-back top-15 fantasy seasons, including a 2023 campaign in which he produced a career-high 1,342 yards (seventh among WRs) and ranked top 5 at the position in yards per reception, yards per target and yards per route run. Even prior to the injury, however, Aiyuk was underperforming last season, scoring zero TDs and reaching double-digit fantasy points once in seven games. Aiyuk is still in his prime at age 27, but it's unclear when he'll return, how effective he'll be, and how much work he'll be given in a fairly crowded offense. Aiyuk is only worth late-round consideration in deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Braelon Allen enters Week 1 for the Jets in search of a breakout against the Steelers. All reports indicate he's in line for a split with Breece Hall rather than being a backup. Given that the Jets figure to be one of the heaviest rushing teams in the league with Justin Fields under center, there's likely room for to coexist. It's a bit of a leap of faith to deploy Allen as a flex option in this opener until his usage is visible, but a matchup against a defense that allowed 4.3 yards per carry last season isn't one from which to immediately shy away.
outlooksByWeek.2: Braelon Allen hopes to improve his efficiency for the Jets in Week 2 against the Bills. While Allen scored on an eight-yard run in Week 1, he ended with nine yards on six carries while Breece Hall topped 100 yards while averaging better than five yards per carry. Much of the offseason talk was about a split backfield, but for one week, Allen looks like a touchdown vulture at best, even in a run heavy Jets attack. Buffalo allowed 160 yards and two touchdowns on the ground last week, but Allen will need to show it before he can be trusted as a reliable flex option.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen is back for Year 2 in New York after soaking up 111 touches as a rookie. The 2024 fourth-round pick quickly stepped into a change-of-pace role behind Breece Hall and was utilized as both a rusher (5.4 carries per game) and receiver (1.7 targets per game). His efficiency wasn't overly impressive (3.6 YPC, 5.1 YPT) and he eventually deferred some work to 2024 fifth-rounder Isaiah Davis, but it's notable that he's still one of the league's youngest backs at 21-years-old. Despite speculation of a committee approach, Hall figures to remain the lead, or at least 1A' back this season, with Allen and Davis battling for the rest of the touches. That won't be enough for consistent fantasy output. Allen is only worth a late pick in deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.2: Davis Allen will look to get back into the end zone for the Rams in Week 2 against Tennessee after logging the team's only TD through the air in a season-opening win against the Texans. Allen's TD came on a 13-yard connection with Matthew Stafford, though it was Allen's only catch (on two targets) in the game. Starting tight end Tyler Higbee didn't see any targets, but he out-snapped Allen 35-22, so the pecking order likely remains the same, with Higbee on top. The Titans didn't allow any Broncos TE to tally more than three receptions or 21 yards in Week 1.

outlooksByWeek.1: Josh Allen begins his 2025 campaign with a potentially challenging Week 1 matchup Sunday night when the Bills host the Ravens. Baltimore's defense was surprisingly vulnerable to opposing quarterbacks last season, allowing the eighth most fantasy points per game, but they also held Allen to just 307 yards and no touchdowns in two meetings, including the playoffs. Allen's rushing ability makes him an every week starter, but expectations can be somewhat tempered out of the gate.
outlooksByWeek.2: John Allen will seek a repeat of a monster outing in Week 2 when the Bills travel to face the Jets. Allen accounted for 424 total yards and four touchdowns and now takes aim at a defense that allowed four touchdown passes in Week 1, and one that he put up six touchdowns against in two meetings last season. While you wouldn't expect this game to be as much of a shootout, Allen remains locked in as a top quarterback option that's highly likely to produce the majority of his team's scoring.

player.seasonOutlook: The reigning NFL MVP is back for his eighth season, having finished each of the last five as the No. 1 or No. 2 fantasy QB. Though he wasn't asked to throw as often last season (482 attempts ranked 14th and marked his fewest since 2019), Allen substantially cut down on turnovers (career-low five INTs) and remained a major force with his legs (he's finished top 5 among QBs in carries and rush TDs in all seven seasons). Still in his prime at age 29, Allen's dual-threat ability and a solid, slightly improved supporting cast sets him up for another elite fantasy campaign in 2025.

outlooksByWeek.1: Keenan Allen was traded to the Bears last offseason, ending an 11-year stint with the Chargers, but the move didn't do the veteran wideout's production any favors. Over 15 regular-season games he managed a 70-744-7 line, solid numbers but still a significant step back from 2023, and his 6.1 yards per target was a career low. Allen elected to return to the Bolts in free agency, reuniting with quarterback Justin Herbert, but he'll be firmly behind Ladd McConkey in the pecking order for targets and working in Jim Harbaugh's run-heavy scheme, so he's unlikely to recapture his former level of production. In a Week 1 trip to Sao Paulo, Allen will face a Kansas City secondary that ranked sixth in receiving yards allowed to WRs, but tied for 24th in receiving TDs allowed to the position.
outlooksByWeek.2: Keenan Allen made an impressive return to the Chargers, turning a team-high 10 targets into seven catches for 68 yards and a touchdown. Ladd McConkey is still the team's no. 1 WR and Quentin Johnston remains arguably Justin Herbert's favorite option in the end zone, so most of Allen's damage seems likely to come between the 20s. That would limit his ceiling in a Jim Harbaugh/Greg Roman-helmed offense that still figures to prioritize the ground game. Allen will face a familiar foe in Week 2, taking on a Raiders secondary that ranked a respectable 10th in fantasy points per game allowed to WRs last season, but which he has a 1,178 career receiving yards against, more than any other team in the NFL.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen is back with the Chargers (the team he was with for his first 11 pro seasons) after spending last season in Chicago. During that 2024 campaign, Allen handled a hefty 26.9% target share (7.9 per game), which ranked 11th among receivers, during 15 active weeks. His efficiency took a big hit from his Los Angeles years (most Chicago pass catchers had this issue), but he did find the end zone seven times and has now scored between six and eight TDs in seven of his last eight seasons. Allen is now 33-years-old (ancient for an NFL receiver) and hasn't played a full regular season since 2019. He's no longer a fantasy WR1 (he finished 34th in PPG last season), but he has a real shot to trail only Ladd McConkey in targets in a solid Los Angeles offense. Allen is a fine late-round flier for your bench and has WR3/flex upside.

outlooksByWeek.2: LeQuint Allen and fellow rookie Bhayshul Tuten are set to split backup duties behind Travis Etienne in Week 2 against the Bengals after the Jaguars traded Tank Bigsby to the Eagles on Monday. Allen was drafted three rounds later than Tuten as a seventh-round selection out of Syracuse. Tuten had three touches to Allen's two in Week 1, while Etienne led Jacksonville's backfield with 19 touches.

player.seasonOutlook: Allen was selected by the Jaguars in the seventh round of April's draft. His rushing efficiency at Syracuse is concerning (class-low 4.5 YPC), but he has the biggest hands in this RB class and his 83 targets and 64 receptions last season were tops in this RB class. He'll look to carve out a third-down role in the pros, but it may take a while, as Travis Etienne Jr., Tank Bigsby and fourth-round rookie Bhayshul Tuten top the Jacksonville depth chart.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyler Allgeier opens the 2024 season as Bijan Robinson's primary backup in a Week 1 matchup against the Buccaneers. Robinson had most of Atlanta's backfield touches and passing game involvement as a RB last season, and that is not set to change this campaign. Allgeier did still prove to be a skilled back when needed last year, but the skills of his teammate have been shown to be more effective against defenses in the NFL. This makes Allgeier not likely to have a huge impact fantasy-wise this season or against a tough Tampa Bay front, unless Robinson were to suffer an injury.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tyler Allgeier will aim to register meaningful carries for the Falcons in Week 2 against the Vikings. Allgeier finished with just two fewer carries than star rusher Bijan Robinson against the Buccaneers in Week 1, but Robinson outpaced his backfield mate with seven more targets in the passing game. This makes it very likely that Allgeier's role moving forward will be as a supplementary rusher. He should still register a solid number of carries in Minnesota, against a defense that gave up 119 total rushing yards to the Bears in Monday Night Football.

player.seasonOutlook: Allgeier is entering his fourth NFL season, including his third straight as Bijan Robinson's backup/running mate. With Robinson taking on a larger role in 2024, Allgeier hit career-low marks in snap share (28%), carries (137) and targets (13). He cleared 12 touches only once (an 18-point win in Week 6), which was also his only game with more than 12.3 fantasy points. The 25-year-old clearly has no standalone fantasy value and, though he's limited as a pass catcher, he'd certainly be positioned for a hefty chunk of Atlanta's carries in the event of a Robinson injury. Allgeier is a fine late-round insurance flier.

outlooksByWeek.1: Mark Andrews had a disastrous Divisional Round playoff performance against Buffalo, but he'll immediately have a chance for redemption as the Ravens take on the Bills in Week 1. He saw his snaps and targets cut dramatically on a per-game basis in 2025, but he propped up his fantasy production with an impressive 11 touchdowns. Andrews will also probably have a clearer path to targets to start the season, with Isaiah Likely (knee) looking unlikely to suit up. Andrews is touchdown-dependent, but he's a still a low-end TE1 for the opening week of the season.
outlooksByWeek.2: Mark Andrews benefitted from being the Ravens' primary pass-catching tight end in Week 1 with Isaiah Likely (foot) sidelined. Andrews was on the field for 38 of 51 offensive snaps, but he still commanded only one target. A Week 2 matchup against Cleveland isn't likely to force Baltimore into a pass-heavy gameplan, meaning Andrews is likely to see limited targets once again. Even if Likely remains sidelined, there should be better starting tight ends available.

player.seasonOutlook: Andrews is a tricky evaluation after an odd career turn in 2024 in which he was fortunate to finish eighth in fantasy PPG after posting top-5 finishes the prior five seasons. After handling a target share in the 22-to-28% range during 2019-23 (all were top 4 at the position), Andrews dipped to 15% in 2024 (20th) and finished 20th in targets, 14th in catches, ninth in yards and first in TDs among tight ends. Andrews has always been extremely efficient when targeted (he's never finished lower than fifth in YPRR), but he's also never been quite as TD dependent (11 TDs in 2024 were a career high and his 16.2% TD rate was way above his prior career rate of 7.1%). Andrews was bailed out by the TD outlier and will need to bounce back in the target area in order to return to elite TE1 production.

outlooksByWeek.1: Elijah Arroyo is set to make his NFL regular-season debut for Seattle in Week 1 against the 49ers. The second-round draft selection is tentatively slated to work behind AJ Barner in the tight end pecking order, though the two will likely battle for snaps throughout the campaign. Arroyo is just one part of a new-look Seahawks passing game that includes numerous other additions, including QB Sam Darnold and wideouts Cooper Kupp and rookie Tory Horton. The 49ers aren't an ideal matchup, as their defense allowed the fourth-fewest passing yards in the NFL last year.

player.seasonOutlook: Arroyo was selected by Seattle in the second round of April's draft. A seam stretcher, Arroyo's 10.0 aDOT last season at Miami ranked second and his 16.9 YPR and 12.6 YPT first in this TE class. He also led this class in YPR, YPT, RAC and adjusted catch rate for his career. Incredibly, Arroyo is charted as having zero career drops. The important context here is that Arroyo was a rarely used target (61 in 34 games, 47 of which came in 2024). He has long-term fantasy upside, but will open his career battling second-year A.J. Barner for work. Arroyo is the better pass-catching prospect of the two, so he's a sleeper to consider in the late rounds of deep leagues.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tutu Atwell and the Rams will begin the regular season with a Week 1 matchup versus the Texans. Atwell could find it difficult to get targets this year, as Los Angeles brought in Davante Adams to feature alongside Puka Nacua as one of the most dynamic WR duos in the league. Atwell managed to register 13.4 YPC on 42 catches during the regular season last year, though he wasn't able to get into the end zone. Houston allowed 7.69 yards per target to wideouts last year, ninth-fewest in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tutu Atwell will look to make more noise in the Rams' Week 2 matchup versus Tennessee after a quiet regular-season opener. Against Houston in Week 1, Atwell caught just one pass (on one target) for four yards. Meanwhile, top WRs Puka Nacua and Davante Adams combined for 14 catches for 181 yards. Given the talent between that pair, Atwell may find it hard to get involved on a weekly basis. The Titans faced Denver in Week 1 and surrendered a modest 120 yards to wideouts.

player.seasonOutlook: Atwell re-signed with the Rams during the offseason and is set to enter his fifth season with the team. The 2021 second-round pick has seen a progressive increase in receptions and yardage during each pro season, though he hasn't quite lived up to his Day 2 draft selection pedigree. Atwell has yet to post a top-60 fantasy campaign and, after failing to find the end zone in 2024, he has a total of five scores in 54 career games. Sean McVay has said that he will deploy Atwell more often moving forward, but the undersized 25-year-old remains well behind Puka Nacua and Davante Adams in terms of target priority. Atwell is not a fantasy option.

outlooksByWeek.1: Brandon Aubrey was one of the best kickers in the NFL last season for the Cowboys. Aubrey connected on 40 field goals; only Pittsburgh kicker Chris Boswell had more. Aubrey also hit 14 field goals of at least 50 yards, which was tops in the league. The Dallas offense returns its quarterback as well as all its playmakers on the outside, and also added the dynamic George Pickens as a deep threat. The Cowboys should be involved in their fair share of shootouts this season.  The Week 1 matchup is unkind, though; the Cowboys will face the defending champion Philadelphia Eagles on Thursday. The Eagles allowed just 17.8 points per tilt in 2024, which was second in the NFL.
outlooksByWeek.2: Brandon Aubrey connected on two field goals and two extra points in the season opener for Dallas. Aubrey is an outstanding 25-of-28 on field goals of 50-plus yards for his career. Aubrey should remain busy in Week 2 versus the Giants. New York allowed 21 points in their season opener, and Aubrey connected on at least two field goals and two extra points in each of the two matchups with the G-Men last season.

outlooksByWeek.1: Calvin Austin became a bigger part of the Pittsburgh offense in the 2024 season, doubling his reception total (36) and tripling his yardage (548). He's likely too small to emerge as reliable outside receiver, something the Steelers hope Roman Wilson can achieve, but Austin should keep his role as the team's primary slot receiver. The problem is that the Steelers will likely play with multiple tight ends or running backs often, potentially limiting how often Austin is on the field. He's not a reliable fantasy option in Week 1 against the Jets.
outlooksByWeek.2: Calvin Austin was projected to begin the season as Pittsburgh's No. 2 wide receiver, though there was some doubt about his ability to hold off Roman Wilson for the role. Those doubts were put to rest in Week 1, as he played 45 of 56 snaps and tied for second on the team with six targets. Austin broke free for a long touchdown, though he more notably made a leaping, contested catch on a back shoulder throw from Aaron Rodgers. Austin will be prioritized for targets behind DK Metcalf and potentially Jonnu Smith, but he could burst onto the fantasy radar in standard-sized leagues with another impressive showing in Week 2 against Seattle.

outlooksByWeek.1: Elic Ayomanor will make his NFL debut in Week 1 against the sturdy Denver defense. It's hard to pinpoint exactly where Ayomanor stands on Tennessee's WR depth chart. Calvin Ridley's locked in on top, but the ordering is murky between Ayomanor, Tyler Lockett, Van Jefferson and Chimere Dike, none of whom were on the team last season. Lockett and Jefferson are veterans, while Dike was selected earlier than Ayomanor in the fourth round of the 2025 NFL Draft. It may take Ayomanor a few games to separate from the pack, so he's hardly more than a bench stash for Week 1, but he has a chance to eventually emerge as the No. 2 option behind Ridley for rookie QB Cam Ward.
outlooksByWeek.2: Elic Ayomanor ranked second on the Titans with seven Week 1 targets but turned them into just two catches for 13 yards as rookie QB Cam Ward threw for just 112 yards. Ayomanor's usage was encouraging, as the rookie fourth-round pick looks like the No. 2 WR for Tennessee behind Calvin Ridley, but the team's whole passing game is probably best avoided in Week 2 against a Rams defense that held Houston without a TD in Week 1. Ayomanor's worth stashing on the bench in dynasty and keeper formats, and he could even provide some redraft value down the line if Ward improves.

player.seasonOutlook: Ayomanor was selected by the Titans in the fourth round of April's draft. He sports a solid size/speed combo, though he lacks some short-area burst (as shown by his class-worst 1.58 10-yard split at the combine). That didn't slow him from a huge workload at Stanford, as he handled a 32% target share and 47% air yard share (second highest in this class) last season. His efficiency was mostly below average, but there's potential here. Ayomanor will begin his career competing with Tyler Lockett and Van Jefferson (among others) for work behind Calvin Ridley. Ayomanor is only worth drafting in deep leagues and dynasty.

outlooksByWeek.1: Saquon Barkley is coming off one of the best seasons in NFL history for a running back, and the matchup of the Eagles versus the Dallas Cowboys in Week 1 of the 2025 campaign should have Saquon licking his chops.  The Cowboys allowed 137.1 yards per tilt on the ground in 2024, which was 29th in the league.  Barkley rushed for 167 yards in one of the two clashes with Dallas last season.  The Cowboys traded Micah Parsons and gained back run-stuffer Kenny Clark in the deal, though giving up one of the most dynamic players in the game today is unlikely to help the Dallas defense in the short term.
outlooksByWeek.2: Saquon Barkley was fairly quiet by his standards in the season opener for the Eagles. Barkley rushed 18 times for 60 yards and a touchdown, while also catching four passes for 24 yards out of the backfield. Barkley had just three games all of last season in which he failed to gain at least 100 yards from scrimmage. Saquon will look to get back on track in Week 2 in a Super Bowl rematch against Kansas City. The AFC powerhouse allowed just 90 rushing yards in its season opener, though was torched through the air by Justin Herbert of the Chargers. As a result, Barkley's involvement in the passing game may be more fruitful than his forays on the ground. Barkley caught six passes for 40 yards in last year's Super Bowl, while only averaging 2.3 yards per rush out of the backfield.

player.seasonOutlook: Barkley's first season with the Eagles started with a three-touchdown debut and never lost steam en route to a Super Bowl LIX victory and NFL Offensive Player of the Year honors. Despite resting at times (including all of Week 18), Barkley led the NFL in carries, touches and scrimmage yards, which led to a position-best 22.2 fantasy PPG. Barkley, who averaged a career-best 5.8 YPC, does carry some risk, though, as he enters his age-28 campaign off a season with an absurd 482 touches (including the playoffs). He'll need to sustain his elite rushing output, as he isn't a big factor in the passing game (outside the top 25 in targets, catches and yards). He nonetheless remains in a great spot behind the Eagles' terrific offensive line and should be off the board in the first round of fantasy drafts.

outlooksByWeek.1: AJ Barner will begin his second NFL campaign with Seattle in a Week 1 matchup versus San Francisco. The Michigan product served as the Seahawks No. 2 tight end behind Noah Fant last year, but with Fant now out of the picture, Barner could take on a starting role. With that being said, Seattle drafted Elijah Arroyo in the second round of April's NFL Draft, and he could provide legitimate competition for Barner. The 49ers were tough against tight ends last year, giving up a modest 40.1 receiving yards per game, sixth-fewest in the league.
outlooksByWeek.2: AJ Barner goes into Week 2 against Pittsburgh having established himself as Seattle's top tight end ahead of rookie Elijah Arroyo. In Week 1 against the 49ers, Barner logged 44 of Seattle's 52 offensive snaps to Arroyo's 16. However, Barner caught just one pass for zero yards and served mainly as a blocker, so a continued big snap share may not translate into significant production. Pittsburgh contained Jets tight ends in a Week 1 win, holding them to three catches for 36 yards.

outlooksByWeek.1: Tyler Bass should again provide the Bills with steady scoring production, starting in Week 1 against the Ravens. Bass has posted identical 24-for-29 field goal results over the past two seasons, and had a career-high 64 extra point attempts last year in this prolific offense. While Bass had just 13 points in two meetings with Baltimore a season ago, the game's high 50.5 point total suggests he'll have ample scoring chances.
outlooksByWeek.2: Tyler Bass won't face the Jets in Week 2 after the Bills placed him on IR prior to last week's opener. Bass will miss at least three more games due to groin/hip issues while Matt Prater assumes kicking duties.
